From 0c5e37ad2e2d416867949f22f5a3704737e9e856 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: DRAFT <draft@example.com>
Date: Mon, 4 May 2026 09:51:16 +0000
Subject: [DRAFT PATCH v2] ssb / bcma / firmware: SROM revision 11 support
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

DRAFT — derived primarily from a single BCM4352-family board
(DSL-3580L); see sprom-rev11/README.md in the proposal repository for
the data set and provenance, and sprom-rev11/cross_check.md for the
status of cross-validation against canonical Broadcom layout. Not for
upstream submission until:

 - the IL0MAC vs. CCODE word overlap exposed by the bcm4360usb
   cross-board test vector is resolved (SSB_SPROM11_IL0MAC=0x90 and
   SSB_SPROM8_CCODE=0x92 share word 0x92; one of the two is wrong
   for rev 11 -- see Finding 1 in sprom-rev11/cross_check.md);

 - a second rev-11 board with non-zero values in the all-zero region
   (byte 0x190..0x1B0) confirms the offsets pinned here.

The bcm4360usb reference NVRAM (defaultsromvars_4360usb in
asuswrt-merlin / hynnet / landonf, rev 11, BCM4360 USB -- same chip
family as the DSL-3580L target) has been added as a second test
vector under sprom-rev11/harness/vectors/. It exercises ANTAVAIL,
TXRXC, SUBBAND5GVER, the per-chain block stride (chains 0 and 1) and
the rxgains bit-packing on a non-saturated triplet (triso=9), all of
which round-trip cleanly. Its principal new finding is the IL0MAC
overlap above.

This is a single-patch consolidation of three logically independent
changes that nevertheless need to land together to be useful:

 1. struct ssb_sprom is extended with the rev-11 fields demonstrated
    by an on-device 'wl dump nvram' on a BCM4352-family board:
    per-band rxgains triplets, the front-end-module / PA control
    block, mcsbw80*po / mcsbw160*po / mcslr*po, the sb20in*/sb40and80
    hr/lr matrix, dot11agdup{hr,lr}po, dot11agofdmhrbw202gpo /
    ofdmlrbw202gpo, and per-chain pdoffset arrays. The per-chain
    power info struct gains rev-11-shaped maxp2ga, maxp5ga[4],
    pa2ga[3], pa5ga[12]. All additions are appended; no offset
    shift on existing fields, no ABI break for any in-tree consumer
    of struct ssb_sprom.

 2. drivers/firmware/broadcom/bcm47xx_sprom.c gains NVRAM key->field
    mappings for the new rev-11 fields and a new path-style helper
    bcm47xx_fill_sprom_path_r11 for the per-chain comma-separated
    arrays (rxgains*, pa5ga[12], maxp5ga[4]). This is the SoC-router
    side: BCM47xx / BCM53xx boards expose these fields via NVRAM
    rather than raw SROM, and the existing bcm47xx_sprom_fill_auto
    pattern is extended mechanically.

 3. drivers/bcma/sprom.c gets bcma_sprom_extract_r11(), dispatched
    from bcma_sprom_get() when the SPROM revision word reads as 11.
    The extractor decodes:

      - boardrev at the rev-8 offset (0x82) -- verified;
      - IL0MAC, ANTAVAIL and TXRXC at rev-11-specific offsets
        (0x90 / 0xA0 / 0xA8). v1 of this patch reused the rev-8
        positions for these three; an offline differential test
        ('wl srdump' decoded by the parser vs. 'wl nvram_dump' as
        oracle) on the DSL-3580L falsified that assumption: the
        nominal values for aa{2,5}g, txchain/rxchain/antswitch and
        the SROM-side MAC appeared at offsets shifted past the
        rev-8 positions. Three new SSB_SPROM11_* offset constants
        are introduced; the bitfield masks/shifts are unchanged
        (the field layout within each word is the same as rev 8,
        only the absolute offset moved);
      - subband5gver at byte 0xD6;
      - per-chain power info blocks at 0xD8 / 0x100 / 0x128
        (stride 0x28), full layout: maxp2ga, pa2ga[3], rxgains
        pack [2 x u16], maxp5ga[4 packed], pa5ga[12];
      - the rxgains bit-packing
            byte = (trelnabyp << 7) | (triso << 3) | elnagain
        with byte-to-sub-band assignment
            RXGAINS0 lo=5gm, hi=5gh
            RXGAINS1 lo=2g,  hi=5gl(UNII-1)
        verified by cross-reference of `wl srdump` against
        `wl nvram_dump`. Three of the four reference bytes are
        saturated/zero on the DSL-3580L, so 5gl=0xb3 is the only
        fully informative data point on that board; on the
        bcm4360usb second vector the encoding round-trips on the
        non-saturated triplets (3, 9, 1) [5 GHz] and (4, 9, 1)
        [2.4 GHz] for both populated chains, which exercises every
        bit position;
      - per-chain pdoffset40ma triplet at byte 0xCA;
      - the rev-11 power-per-rate region (byte 0x150..0x190).
        Layout differs from rev 9: each 5 GHz sub-band has four
        consecutive u32 entries (mcsbw20/40/80/160) rather than
        two, and a pair of u16 (dot11agofdmhrbw202gpo,
        ofdmlrbw202gpo) sits between the 2.4 GHz BW40 entry and
        the 5 GHz BW20 entries. Byte offsets are pinned by
        value-match against the NVRAM dump.

    Fields landing in the all-zero residual region (byte
    0x190..0x1B0 -- mcslr*po, sb20in40/sb20in80and160/sb40and80
    hr/lr, dot11agdup{hr,lr}po, pdoffset80ma) cannot be
    disambiguated by value-match from a single dump; they are
    listed as TODO and remain reachable only via the bcm47xx_sprom
    NVRAM fallback until a second board pins them.

The dispatcher uses a switch on the SROM revision read from the raw
buffer (rather than bus->sprom.revision, which is populated later).
For revisions <= 10 the existing extract_r8 path is preserved
verbatim; the default arm in the switch is exactly the prior call.

Reference dump (raw + nominal) and full provenance documentation
live in router-data/wl1_srom_raw.txt and router-data/wl1_nvram.txt
of the proposal repository; sprom-rev11/README.md catalogs the
single-board provenance, the open verification points, and the
review path expected on linux-wireless.

An offline differential-test harness for the extractor lives at
sprom-rev11/harness/ (compiles bcma_sprom_extract_r11 in userspace
with a small kernel shim, runs it against the committed test
vector, diffs every populated field against the corresponding
NVRAM nominal). Two run modes:

 - default: srom_dump + nvram_dump pair from a real board
   ('wl srdump' + 'wl nvram_dump'). Used for the DSL-3580L vector
   committed under router-data/. Exposed the rev-11 offset shift of
   IL0MAC / ANTAVAIL / TXRXC fixed in this v2.

 - synth (--synth FILE): NVRAM-only round-trip. Synthesizes a raw
   SROM from the NVRAM using this patch's offsets/encoding, runs the
   parser against it, diffs back. Used for the bcm4360usb reference
   NVRAM, where no raw 'wl srdump' is available. Exposed the IL0MAC
   vs. CCODE word overlap recorded as the first pre-upstream blocker
   above.

Reviewers and contributors of new test vectors can use either path
to flag any further per-board divergence before bring-up. Canonical
cross-checks against Broadcom's bcmsrom_tbl.h (the authoritative
SROM layout table, GPLv2-with-linking-exception in bcmdhd /
asuswrt-merlin / StreamUnlimited mirrors) are tracked in
sprom-rev11/cross_check.md.

Signed-off-by: TBD <tbd@example.com>
---
 drivers/bcma/sprom.c                      | 227 +++++++++++++++++++++-
 drivers/firmware/broadcom/bcm47xx_sprom.c | 175 ++++++++++++++++-
 include/linux/ssb/ssb.h                   |  96 +++++++++
 include/linux/ssb/ssb_regs.h              |  82 ++++++++
 4 files changed, 577 insertions(+), 3 deletions(-)

diff --git a/drivers/bcma/sprom.c b/drivers/bcma/sprom.c
index e668ad7..cbe79dc 100644
--- a/drivers/bcma/sprom.c
+++ b/drivers/bcma/sprom.c
@@ -474,6 +474,220 @@ static void bcma_sprom_extract_r8(struct bcma_bus *bus, const u16 *sprom)
 	     SSB_SPROM8_TEMPDELTA_HYSTERESIS_SHIFT);
 }
 
+/*
+ * SROM revision 11 extractor — DRAFT, partial coverage.
+ *
+ * This routine is a companion to bcma_sprom_extract_r8 for the rev-11
+ * SROM layout introduced with the BCM4352 / BCM4360 family. Coverage
+ * is derived by direct cross-reference of the raw `wl srdump` output
+ * against the nominal `wl nvram_dump` output of a BCM4352-family
+ * board (DSL-3580L, see sprom-rev11/README.md in the proposal
+ * repository for the full data set).
+ *
+ * Coverage status:
+ *   - boardrev (SSB_SPROM8_BOARDREV, byte 0x82) shares its byte
+ *     offset with rev 8 on the reference board — verified.
+ *   - IL0MAC, ANTAVAIL, TXRXC sit at rev-11-specific offsets
+ *     (0x90, 0xA0, 0xA8) introduced as SSB_SPROM11_* below. The
+ *     rev-8 positions are NOT correct for rev 11 on this board:
+ *     v1 of this patch reused them and an offline differential
+ *     test against `wl nvram_dump` showed wrong values being
+ *     extracted. Bitfield masks/shifts are reused from rev 8
+ *     because the field layout within each word is unchanged,
+ *     only the absolute byte offset moved.
+ *   - subband5gver, per-chain power info blocks (maxp2ga, pa2ga,
+ *     maxp5ga, pa5ga, rxgains pack), pdoffset40ma, and the
+ *     power-per-rate region (cckbw202gpo, mcsbw{20,40,80,160}{2g,
+ *     5gl,5gm,5gh}po, dot11agofdmhrbw202gpo, ofdmlrbw202gpo) are
+ *     extracted via SSB_SPROM11_* offsets verified by cross-reference.
+ *   - The rxgains bit-packing has been determined and is decoded
+ *     here; see the comment block at the rxgains decode site.
+ *   - A residual region (byte 0x190..0x1B0) reads all zero on the
+ *     reference board, leaving offset disambiguation by value-match
+ *     impossible from a single dump. Fields landing in that region
+ *     (mcslr*po, sb20in*, sb40and80*, dot11agdup*po, pdoffset80ma,
+ *     and the femctrl context block) are marked TODO at the end of
+ *     this function and remain reachable only via the bcm47xx_sprom
+ *     NVRAM fallback path until a second rev-11 board pins them.
+ *
+ * If a future rev-11 board contradicts the offsets pinned here, a
+ * divergent extraction path will be needed; for now the assumption
+ * (single-board derivation) is stated explicitly rather than hidden
+ * in code.
+ */
+static void bcma_sprom_unpack_rxgains(struct ssb_sprom_rxgains *out,
+				      int chain, u8 packed)
+{
+	/* Per-byte rxgains encoding (verified on DSL-3580L, all chains):
+	 * bit 7    = trelnabyp (T/R-eLNA bypass select)
+	 * bits 6:3 = triso     (T/R isolation, 4-bit code)
+	 * bits 2:0 = elnagain  (eLNA gain stage select, 3-bit code)
+	 *
+	 * Each chain carries its own rxgains pack in its per-chain power
+	 * info block; the same encoding applies across chains. The
+	 * struct ssb_sprom_rxgains target carries one slot per chain
+	 * (see include/linux/ssb/ssb.h).
+	 */
+	out->trelnabyp[chain] = (packed >> 7) & 0x01;
+	out->triso[chain]     = (packed >> 3) & 0x0f;
+	out->elnagain[chain]  =  packed       & 0x07;
+}
+
+static void bcma_sprom_extract_r11(struct bcma_bus *bus, const u16 *sprom)
+{
+	static const u16 r11_pwr_info_offset[] = {
+		SSB_SPROM11_PWR_INFO_CORE0,
+		SSB_SPROM11_PWR_INFO_CORE1,
+		SSB_SPROM11_PWR_INFO_CORE2,
+	};
+	u16 v;
+	int i;
+
+	/* --- Header (shared layout with rev 8) ------------------------ */
+	for (i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
+		v = sprom[SPOFF(SSB_SPROM11_IL0MAC) + i];
+		*(((__be16 *)bus->sprom.il0mac) + i) = cpu_to_be16(v);
+	}
+
+	SPEX(board_rev, SSB_SPROM8_BOARDREV, ~0, 0);
+	SPEX(board_type, SSB_SPROM1_SPID, ~0, 0);
+
+	SPEX(country_code, SSB_SPROM8_CCODE, ~0, 0);
+	SPEX(ant_available_a, SSB_SPROM11_ANTAVAIL, SSB_SPROM8_ANTAVAIL_A,
+	     SSB_SPROM8_ANTAVAIL_A_SHIFT);
+	SPEX(ant_available_bg, SSB_SPROM11_ANTAVAIL, SSB_SPROM8_ANTAVAIL_BG,
+	     SSB_SPROM8_ANTAVAIL_BG_SHIFT);
+
+	SPEX(txchain, SSB_SPROM11_TXRXC, SSB_SPROM8_TXRXC_TXCHAIN,
+	     SSB_SPROM8_TXRXC_TXCHAIN_SHIFT);
+	SPEX(rxchain, SSB_SPROM11_TXRXC, SSB_SPROM8_TXRXC_RXCHAIN,
+	     SSB_SPROM8_TXRXC_RXCHAIN_SHIFT);
+	SPEX(antswitch, SSB_SPROM11_TXRXC, SSB_SPROM8_TXRXC_SWITCH,
+	     SSB_SPROM8_TXRXC_SWITCH_SHIFT);
+
+	/* --- 5 GHz sub-band layout descriptor ------------------------- */
+	SPEX(subband5gver, SSB_SPROM11_SUBBAND5GVER, 0x00ff, 0);
+
+	/* --- Per-chain power info blocks ------------------------------ *
+	 * Stride 0x28 bytes. Layout verified against the DSL-3580L dump.
+	 * Only 3 chains (rev 11 maxes out at 3-stream), unlike rev 8's 4. */
+	BUILD_BUG_ON(ARRAY_SIZE(r11_pwr_info_offset) >
+		     ARRAY_SIZE(bus->sprom.core_pwr_info));
+
+	for (i = 0; i < ARRAY_SIZE(r11_pwr_info_offset); i++) {
+		struct ssb_sprom_core_pwr_info *p = &bus->sprom.core_pwr_info[i];
+		u16 base = r11_pwr_info_offset[i];
+		int j;
+
+		p->maxp2ga = sprom[SPOFF(base + SSB_SPROM11_PWR_MAXP2GA)] & 0x00ff;
+
+		for (j = 0; j < 3; j++)
+			p->pa2ga[j] = sprom[SPOFF(base + SSB_SPROM11_PWR_PA2GA) + j];
+
+		/* maxp5ga[4] is two consecutive u16 holding 4 × u8 packed
+		 * little-endian: word_lo = (maxp5ga[1] << 8) | maxp5ga[0],
+		 * word_hi = (maxp5ga[3] << 8) | maxp5ga[2]. */
+		v = sprom[SPOFF(base + SSB_SPROM11_PWR_MAXP5GA)];
+		p->maxp5ga[0] = v & 0x00ff;
+		p->maxp5ga[1] = (v >> 8) & 0x00ff;
+		v = sprom[SPOFF(base + SSB_SPROM11_PWR_MAXP5GA) + 1];
+		p->maxp5ga[2] = v & 0x00ff;
+		p->maxp5ga[3] = (v >> 8) & 0x00ff;
+
+		for (j = 0; j < 12; j++)
+			p->pa5ga[j] = sprom[SPOFF(base + SSB_SPROM11_PWR_PA5GA) + j];
+
+		/* Rxgains decode. Two consecutive u16 hold the four sub-band
+		 * triplets (eLNA gain, T/R isolation, T/R-eLNA bypass) for
+		 * this chain, packed one byte per sub-band as
+		 *
+		 *   byte = (trelnabyp << 7) | (triso << 3) | elnagain
+		 *
+		 * Byte-to-sub-band assignment (verified by cross-reference of
+		 * `wl srdump` against `wl nvram_dump` on the reference board):
+		 *   word RXGAINS0 low byte  -> 5gm
+		 *   word RXGAINS0 high byte -> 5gh
+		 *   word RXGAINS1 low byte  -> 2g
+		 *   word RXGAINS1 high byte -> 5gl  (UNII-1)
+		 *
+		 * Reference fit on the DSL-3580L dump (chain 0..2 identical):
+		 *   words = 0xffff, 0xb300
+		 *   5gm=(7,15,1)  -> (1<<7)|(15<<3)|7 = 0xff   ✓
+		 *   5gh=(7,15,1)  -> 0xff                       ✓
+		 *   2g =(0, 0,0)  -> 0x00                       ✓
+		 *   5gl=(3, 6,1)  -> (1<<7)|(6<<3)|3  = 0xb3   ✓
+		 *
+		 * Three of the four bytes are saturated (0xff) or zero on the
+		 * reference board, so 5gl=0xb3 is the only fully informative
+		 * data point. The encoding fits all four bytes uniformly and
+		 * the per-chain triplets in NVRAM match the same bytes on
+		 * every chain. A second board with non-saturated 5gm/5gh and
+		 * non-zero 2g rxgains would harden this further; the encoding
+		 * is committed here as the working extraction with that
+		 * caveat noted in sprom-rev11/README.md.
+		 */
+		v = sprom[SPOFF(base + SSB_SPROM11_PWR_RXGAINS0)];
+		bcma_sprom_unpack_rxgains(&bus->sprom.rxgains_5gm, i,  v       & 0xff);
+		bcma_sprom_unpack_rxgains(&bus->sprom.rxgains_5gh, i, (v >> 8) & 0xff);
+		v = sprom[SPOFF(base + SSB_SPROM11_PWR_RXGAINS1)];
+		bcma_sprom_unpack_rxgains(&bus->sprom.rxgains_2g,  i,  v       & 0xff);
+		bcma_sprom_unpack_rxgains(&bus->sprom.rxgains_5gl, i, (v >> 8) & 0xff);
+	}
+
+	/* Per-chain pdoffset40ma triplet (verified — three identical u16
+	 * at byte 0xCA reading 0x3222 on the reference board, matching
+	 * NVRAM pdoffset40ma{0,1,2}=12834). */
+	for (i = 0; i < 3; i++)
+		bus->sprom.pdoffset40ma[i] =
+			sprom[SPOFF(SSB_SPROM11_PDOFFSET40MA) + i];
+
+	/* Power-per-rate region (byte 0x150..0x190) — rev-11 layout, NOT
+	 * the rev-9 inheritance: mcsbw20/40 are followed by mcsbw80/160
+	 * for each 5 GHz sub-band, and a pair of u16 (dot11agofdmhrbw202gpo,
+	 * ofdmlrbw202gpo) sits between the 2.4 GHz BW40 entry and the
+	 * 5 GHz BW20 entries.
+	 *
+	 * Sanity-check anchors on the reference board:
+	 *   cckbw202gpo   = 0  (aa2g==0)
+	 *   mcsbw205glpo  = 0xeca86420   (UNII-1 active)
+	 *   mcsbw1605gXpo = 0  (160 MHz disabled by board profile)
+	 */
+	SPEX(cckbw202gpo,            SSB_SPROM11_CCKBW202GPO,            ~0, 0);
+	SPEX(cckbw20ul2gpo,          SSB_SPROM11_CCKBW20UL2GPO,          ~0, 0);
+	SPEX32(mcsbw202gpo,          SSB_SPROM11_MCSBW202GPO,            ~0, 0);
+	SPEX32(mcsbw402gpo,          SSB_SPROM11_MCSBW402GPO,            ~0, 0);
+	SPEX(dot11agofdmhrbw202gpo,  SSB_SPROM11_DOT11AGOFDMHRBW202GPO,  ~0, 0);
+	SPEX(ofdmlrbw202gpo,         SSB_SPROM11_OFDMLRBW202GPO,         ~0, 0);
+	SPEX32(mcsbw205glpo,         SSB_SPROM11_MCSBW205GLPO,           ~0, 0);
+	SPEX32(mcsbw405glpo,         SSB_SPROM11_MCSBW405GLPO,           ~0, 0);
+	SPEX32(mcsbw805glpo,         SSB_SPROM11_MCSBW805GLPO,           ~0, 0);
+	SPEX32(mcsbw1605glpo,        SSB_SPROM11_MCSBW1605GLPO,          ~0, 0);
+	SPEX32(mcsbw205gmpo,         SSB_SPROM11_MCSBW205GMPO,           ~0, 0);
+	SPEX32(mcsbw405gmpo,         SSB_SPROM11_MCSBW405GMPO,           ~0, 0);
+	SPEX32(mcsbw805gmpo,         SSB_SPROM11_MCSBW805GMPO,           ~0, 0);
+	SPEX32(mcsbw1605gmpo,        SSB_SPROM11_MCSBW1605GMPO,          ~0, 0);
+	SPEX32(mcsbw205ghpo,         SSB_SPROM11_MCSBW205GHPO,           ~0, 0);
+	SPEX32(mcsbw405ghpo,         SSB_SPROM11_MCSBW405GHPO,           ~0, 0);
+	SPEX32(mcsbw805ghpo,         SSB_SPROM11_MCSBW805GHPO,           ~0, 0);
+	SPEX32(mcsbw1605ghpo,        SSB_SPROM11_MCSBW1605GHPO,          ~0, 0);
+
+	/* TODO (still open — region byte 0x190..0x1B0 reads all zero on
+	 * the reference board, so offset disambiguation by value-match is
+	 * not possible from a single dump): mcslr5g{l,m,h}po,
+	 * sb20in40{hr,lr}po, sb20in80and160{hr,lr}5g{l,m,h}po,
+	 * sb40and80{hr,lr}5g{l,m,h}po, dot11agdup{hr,lr}po,
+	 * pdoffset80ma[3]. The bcm47xx_sprom NVRAM fallback path covers
+	 * these on SoC routers; a second rev-11 board with non-zero
+	 * values in any of these fields would let the offsets be pinned
+	 * here too.
+	 *
+	 * Also TODO from the front-end-module context block: femctrl,
+	 * epagain{2g,5g}, pdgain{2g,5g}, tworangetssi{2g,5g},
+	 * papdcap{2g,5g}, tssiposslope{2g,5g}, gainctrlsph,
+	 * pdoffset2g40ma[3], pdoffset2g40mvalid. Same argument.
+	 */
+}
+
 /*
  * Indicates the presence of external SPROM.
  */
@@ -640,7 +854,18 @@ int bcma_sprom_get(struct bcma_bus *bus)
 		bcma_warn(bus, "Invalid SPROM read from the PCIe card, trying to use fallback SPROM\n");
 		err = bcma_fill_sprom_with_fallback(bus, &bus->sprom);
 	} else {
-		bcma_sprom_extract_r8(bus, sprom);
+		/* Dispatch on the SROM revision read by bcma_sprom_valid().
+		 * Rev 11 has a different per-chain power layout (see
+		 * bcma_sprom_extract_r11 above); the existing extract_r8 is
+		 * preserved verbatim for revisions <= 10. */
+		switch (sprom[SPOFF(SSB_SPROM_REVISION)] & SSB_SPROM_REVISION_REV) {
+		case 11:
+			bcma_sprom_extract_r11(bus, sprom);
+			break;
+		default:
+			bcma_sprom_extract_r8(bus, sprom);
+			break;
+		}
 		kfree(sprom);
 	}
 
diff --git a/drivers/firmware/broadcom/bcm47xx_sprom.c b/drivers/firmware/broadcom/bcm47xx_sprom.c
index bca03fd..4453ceb 100644
--- a/drivers/firmware/broadcom/bcm47xx_sprom.c
+++ b/drivers/firmware/broadcom/bcm47xx_sprom.c
@@ -114,6 +114,54 @@ static void nvram_read_u32_2(const char *prefix, const char *name,
 	*val_hi = (val & 0xFFFF0000U) >> 16;
 }
 
+/*
+ * SROM revision 11 stores some per-chain values as comma-separated lists
+ * under a single NVRAM key (e.g. "pa5ga0=0xff4d,0x1690,..."). The two
+ * helpers below parse such CSV payloads into a fixed-length destination
+ * array. Missing or unparseable elements leave the destination unchanged
+ * and emit a single warning rather than aborting the whole read, since
+ * NVRAM content can be malformed on consumer routers and must not crash
+ * the boot path.
+ */
+#define NVRAM_READ_ARRAY(type)						\
+static void nvram_read_ ## type ## _array(const char *prefix,		\
+					  const char *postfix,		\
+					  const char *name,		\
+					  type *val, size_t len,	\
+					  bool fallback)		\
+{									\
+	char buf[256];							\
+	char *ptr, *next;						\
+	int err;							\
+	size_t i = 0;							\
+	type var;							\
+									\
+	err = get_nvram_var(prefix, postfix, name, buf, sizeof(buf),	\
+			    fallback);					\
+	if (err < 0)							\
+		return;							\
+	ptr = strim(buf);						\
+	while (ptr && *ptr && i < len) {				\
+		next = strchr(ptr, ',');				\
+		if (next)						\
+			*next++ = '\0';					\
+		err = kstrto ## type(ptr, 0, &var);			\
+		if (err) {						\
+			pr_warn("can not parse nvram %s%s entry %zu (%s): %d\n",	\
+				name, postfix ? postfix : "", i, ptr, err); \
+		} else {						\
